prj:ScienceGoal.prj:name: Sample A, 41 sources @ 0.2'' resolution
prj:ScienceGoal.prj:note:
Observe 1.3 mm continuum and J=2-1 transitions of CO, 13CO, and C18O simultaneously in 41 targets at 0.2'' resolution.
"Sample A" are protoplanetary disks with known 1.3 mm fluxes > 20 mJy or 870 micron fluxes > 40 mJy.
This science goal will require 2 different array configurations (see Technical Justification box).

prj:TechnicalJustification.prj:justificationText:
The "A Sample" contain bright disks with known 1.3 mm fluxes > 20 mJy and/or 870 microns > 40 mJy. For this sample, we request the highest resolution available in Cycle 2 for 1.3 mm observations, 0.2'', corresponding to 25 AU at 125 pc. We have set "Largest Angular Structure in source" to 5'' to force the OT to perform the observations using two different array configurations. This is done in order to improve the (u-v) coverage of the observations and make sure we can recover all the flux and structures in the disks observed at the highest resolution.
For this sample, we expect to obtain higher S/N per beam (by a factor > 2) in the continuum than achieved in the Ophiuchus survey by Andrews et al. (2009, 2010), the largest imaging survey of disks to date (resolution = 0.3'', rms = 2-3 mJy @ 870 micron flux >75 mJy, # of targets = 17).
Our correlator setup provides high spectral resolution (0.04-0.08 km/s) for the J=2-1 transitions of CO, 13CO, and C18O, and a total bandwidth of 3.9 GHz for continuum observations.
The spectral windows we used for line observations are relatively narrow (~80 km/s), but since the systemic velocity of Ophiuchus members is well established to be 3.9+/-1.7 km/s (Doppmann et al. 2003), we don not expect to miss the lines of any of the targets.
All targets are well within 7 deg of each other and thus can share phase calibrators. The overheads are high simply because our targets are brigth and don't require long exposure times.

prp:ObsProposal.prp:abstract: We propose a band-6 imaging survey to study the gas and dust of the entire population of disks (from Class I to III) identified by Spitzer in Ophiuchus, the closest of the major star-forming regions in the solar neighborhood. We will simultaneously observe 1.3 mm continuum, and the J=2-1 transitions of CO, 13CO, and C18O. Our strategy is to observe each of the 289 targets at at fixed sensitivity and vary the spatial resolution (from 0.2'' to 1'') based on the known or expected 1.3 mm flux. The resulting survey is an order of magnitude larger and deeper than any previous disk imaging program performed to date at (sub)millimeter wavelengths. Yet, thanks to ALMA's unprecedented sensitivity, it can be completed in ~10 hs of observing time (including overheads and calibrations). The survey has three main goals: 1) Trace the evolution of the gas and dust from the Class I to Class III stage, 2) Study the dependence of disk structure on SED Class, stellar properties, and environment, and 3) Investigate the full diversity of structures present in protoplanetary disks. The underlying motivation of the program is to provide much needed observational constraints to planet formation theory.
prp:ObsProposal.prp:scientificCategoryString: Circumstellar disks, exoplanets and the solar system
